* [X] next2: nerves and neurons
* [/] change synapse linkage - VMS based for each input and output
	- [-] gene for number of neuron inputs - float, integer part is used
	- [-] gene for each input vms coord and output coord - these are based on i/o index
		-- these is how synapses will be created ^ (each input binds to the nearest output; outputs can remain unattached)
	- [-] weight gene per each input - index based
	- [X] remove index-based synapse gene
	- [-] all indexes (for inputs/outputs) are floats and integer part is used
	- [X] no more genes for inputs and outputs
	- [X] synapses are only created by synapse gene with inputVMS, outputVMS, weight and priority attributes
		-- the synapse is created from the nearest neuron/sensor at the inputVMS location to the nearest
			neuron at the outputVMS location
	- [X] motors are not linked by synapses, but by old matching mechanism (since one input socket can only be attached to one output)
	- [X] synapses are created between sensors/neurons and neurons
	- [ ] sensors that have no outputs connected to neurons should die (get deactivated) immediately after decoding for performance
	- [X] synapses should be created in two passes:
		-- first decode all offsetted synapse genes and add pairs of <outputSock*, inputSock*> as keys into a map with
			struct SynapseInfo as value (cumulativeValues for weight, priority)
			-- when the same key exists, just update the values
			-- thus more genes can affect the same synapse
		-- second iterate the map and actually create the synapses - create inputSockets and link them to outputSockets
* [X] new Neuron gene creates a neuron in VMS at specified location
	- [X] neurons are only created by the new Neuron gene and will be housed inside the current cell
	- [X] neuron actual VMS coordinate is affected by the VMS offset of the cell that created it
		-- neuron is instantiated right before cell divides, so its final VMS offset is known
	- [X] the Ribosome holds a map of neural gene keys and set<VMScoord> values. If the same gene is re-read in a child cell
		the gene is reinterpreted only if the actual (offsetted) vms coordinate differs from the one already processed, thus
		avoiding collisions
		-- neural genes are added into this map at the end of the decoding of a cell, before division/specialization
		-- NeuronGenes are processed immediately after adding in the map (if not rejected) and instantiate neurons in the current cell.
		-- neuron attrib and synapse genes are processed at the end of the genome decoding, after all neurons have been instantiated.
	- [X] when a cell splits, neurons from the cell are distributed between its children
		-- odd neurons to left and even neurons to right; these neurons are not further affected by the children cells' VMS offsets
	- [X] all synapses (between neurons, or neuron-motor or sensor-neuron) are expressed in VMS coordinates
		-- thus no more neuron indexes
	- [X] all other neural genes (transfer, bias etc) bind to the nearest neuron from their target VMS location
	- [X] VMS is universal across the entire organism, all cells, neurons, sensors and motors share it, altough individual neurons are associated with individual cells for detachment purposes
		- [X] however VMS coordinates are relative to the current cell's VMS offset. Thus a synapse decoded in a cell will have its 
			real VMS values different then the ones encoded in the gene.
* [ ] Change VMS and synapse mechanism - distributed NS and localized neural gene expression
	- the aim is to have a more robust neural system and allow local alterations based on the layout of the phenotype which have
		a smaller change of breaking the entire system
	- [ ] every body part has a default Neuron created inside in the middle of the VMS, with transfer=ONE and no default synapses
		-- this ensures that the neural graph can be connex
	- [ ] all neural genes are interpreted in their local context (the cell they were read from) 
		-- thus neurons can be created only by genes within the cell; neural properties affect only the neurons within the cell
	- [ ] synapse genes can only link neurons from the cell and its immediate neighbours (those linked by joints)
		-- the VMS lookup is restricted to this local scope
	- [ ] synapse genes coordinates are not affected by VMS offset any more (since the neurons they refer to are already offseted)
		-- thus synapse gene coordinate are used as-is
	- [ ] neural genes are only interpreted when read from a specialized cell; cells that divide will ignore neural genes except VMSOffset
	- [ ] each synapse is guaranteed to be created since there is at least 1 (the default) Neuron in each cell
	- [ ] subgraphs of neurons that are not linked to at least a sensor and a motor should be removed for performance reasons
	- this removes the need to inherit neurons when a cell divides
	- no more need for neural gene maps in the Ribosome, just a set of neural genes in the decode context will suffice
	- [ ] change motor nerve linkage mechanism to only lookup neurons from within the motor cell and its immediate neighbours 

* [X] rethink hyperspace to favour most-usefull possibilities - arrange neighbours in a better way
* [/] !!! Rethink growth mechanism - more fractal/division like in order to favour evolution
	- [X] a small change by itself must be able to benefit the bug - current model is not good at this
	- [X] new cell division based system
		-- [X] cell division working prototype
		-- [X] !! implement new mechanism in Ribosome
	- [X] new division parameter genes: angle, ratio, mirror?, reorientate?, level restrictions
		-- [X] ^ these boolean values are encoded in floats +/-
	- [X] cell divides at an angle but its children keep the same orientation, unless reorientate is specified in the division, in which case the children will be reoriented by this angle
	- [X] proteins accumulate per cell, not per segment - no more segments 
	- [X] if proteins yield x*y*z*w = 0, the cell specializes into default type - fat cell body part
	- [X] proteins should have a float weight instead of current int 1
	- [X] division creates bond between child cells (weld/pivot joint)
	- [/] when dividing, each existing bond is either split or inherited by one side:
		-- [X] if division axis is similar to bond direction (angle error < thresh), bond is split and inherited by each side
		-- [X] otherwise each side inherits bonds on its side of the division axis
		-- [X] new BondBias gene that biases the bond inheritance axis towards one side
		-- [ ] result is a graph of cells - use it to find shortest path to route sensor/motor nerves
	- [X] division automatically creates joint (weld or pivot) between child cells as well as muscles (only for pivot joint)
		-- [X] (pivot only) joint's default (rest) orientation is perpendicular to the division axis, going from left child cell to right child cell; it's angle direction is the same as the parent cell (so joint can be mirrored as well)
		-- [X] left and right muscles are defined with respect to the joint's zero-axis (left muscle on the positive side); mirrored joints have left/right switched 
	- [X] when cell splits, part of its mass must be used for joint and muscles (if pivot joint)
		-- [X] original cell is kept for joint/muscle genes and its size is changed to joint size - it's used on the ctor of PivotJoint
	- [X] new muscle parameter genes with left/right restriction per cell - dictate the parameters of the muscles that will be created by the division (only for pivot joint)
	- [X] if division splits the pivot joint, muscles will be duplicated for each resulting joint (depending on mirroring)
	- [X] new VMS offset gene to control offset for a division branch (mirrored trees with same genes must have different coordinates to enable control by different neurons)
		- [-] handle mirrored tree case
			-- there's no sensible way to achieve this, will just let a vms offset gene with branch restriction do the job
				otherwise the two mirrored subtrees will have the same offset
		- [X] VMS offset is inherited into the child cells but the same gene cannot be applied twice in the same cell
			-- so if a cell's VMS offset is already affected by a gene decoded in the parent cell and the same gene is encountered again
				during child decoding, it will be ignored second time
			-- keep a set of vms offset genes into each cell and pass it down to its children
	- [X] division happens when gene decoding reaches the end, so all genes have a chance of being read
		-- [X] !! because of this, attribute gene handling must be redesigned (body part classes don't have the chance to register the attributes any more before the genes are decoded since the body-part classes are instantiated when decoding is finished for the current cell)
	- [X] each cell specializes into a body part depending on hyperspace position or turns into a FatCell (for unused or incomplete positions)
		-- [X] ^ maps of gene-types/values in BodyCell that accumulates the values
		-- [X] once the decoding is done, the body part type is determined and following actions take place:
		-- [X] a map of body-part-type/static methods is used to call the correct method to update the cell's density
		-- [X] another similar map is used to retrieve the future body part's shape and connection points, and all neighbour link positions are updated so that cells will be in the correct position
		-- [X] the correct body part is now instantiated while the cell's position, size, density and shape are all correct.
		-- [X] BodyPart base class uses the cell to retrieve size, density, position, rotation and velocity for PhysicalBody
		-- [X] derived body part classes use the cell's gene maps to retrieve various specific attributes 
		-- [X] unspecialized cells will instantiate a FatCell body part which acts as an energy storage
	- [X] joints and muscles are not created explicitly any more - remove them from hyperspace
	- [X] must rethink muscle linkange and body part hierarchies
	- [ ] must find different way to route sensor and motor lines through neighbouring cells - no more parent hierarchy
	- [X] BodyParts hold a list of all their neighbours - Joints are treated as part of the graph as well, so the BodyParts will actually hold links to joints, not directly to other BodyParts (with the exception of Muscles which are attached directly to the left-side body part)
		-- in this way the mass of the whole body can be easily computed (Joints have mass too) and the whole thing becomes more uniform
	- [X] (not a problem any more) perpendicular division of two adjacent cell problem - square of cells
	- [X] !!! proteins are NOT inherited !!!
	- [X] default child cell genome offset is 0 - same genes as parent
	- [X] new gene child offset left/right which changes the default offset (relatively) of the child cells once the division takes place
	- [X] each cell knows if it's left or right and if it's mirrored
	- [X] new restrictions on genes for left/right
	- [X] all unused positions in hyperspace should be filled up with FatCell
	- [X] no more start marker genes in order to allow for easy variation in offsets
	- [ ] if decoding starts on a STOP gene, it moves forward until the 1st valid gene
	- [X] body attribute genes are read at any depth but only interpreted once - see below
	- [ ] when a joint between cells breaks, all synapses, motor lines and sensor lines passing through it are disconnected
		-- [X] also if some of the cells become isolated from energy sources they die
			-- body parts die when isolated from mouth or egg-layer
		-- [X] after a split, each of the two parts may live on if they have energy
			-- and if they both have mouths and egg-layers
		-- [X] must introduce a default energy drain for each cell regardless if they do work or not, so that parts that are isolated from a mouth will eventually die
	- [X] !!! No more need for a Torso, it'll just be an unspecialized cell (or bone)
	- [ ] tune muscle actuation: max contraction speed + limited range of motion 

